description.text:
I wanted to mount a featherboard on my tablesaw fence. The commercially-available Magswitch bases are way too wide for that, so I made this mini version to get the job done.

Since my printer's bed is too small to print a base the same length as the commercial bases, I designed this mini base so that I could use two of them to mount one of Magswitch's featherboards. To keep things flexible, I added additional bolt slots to accommodate smaller parts with 80mm and 100mm-wide mounting patterns.

To help prevent bolts from flying everywhere when breaking down a jig-setup, and keep the bolts steady once they're inserted, I covered the slots and left an oval hole just big enough to wiggle through the head of a 1/4"-20 carriage bolt.

Magswitch's stock 45 degree risers are intended for use with a base that's mounted on the same level as the workpiece and didn't work well with fence-mounted bases. I designed "magjig_riser_right_angle" to allow featherboards to reach the table surface.

My mini featherboards are designed to attach to these bases: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2284341

title: Y Rod Axis holder for Maxbots Y carriage

description.text: I am moving this design off of Thingiverse in protest of their attempt to patent designs originally conceived by the 3D printing community.

• Print two of them.
  • Install 4 three mm screws in each side, these will be used to secure the rods once they are installed.
  • Mount one of them on one end of the frame.
  • Place the rods and the y-axis in the holes
  • Fit the other holder on the ends of the rods and slowly slide it down into place. If it's extremely tight make sure the rods are going all the way into the holes. You might have to trim the insides just a little to get them to seat all the way. This is why there are screws to secure the rods.
  • Once both ends are bolted into place, measure that they are an even distance from both sides of the frame.
  • Tighten the bolts to the frame.
  • Slide the y-carriage to each end, while it's at that end gently tighten the screws until they are snug. This will ensure the rods are lined up and the carriage moves smoothly.

description.text:
At some point, I purchased a reasonably standard 360W power supply and while the device worked fine, most of the threaded holes in the aluminum enclosure were stripped, right out of the box. One of them even fell out. Also, the panel-mount voltage selection switch was not panel mounted, it was just sitting there loosely near a cutout in the case, supported by nothing more than its soldered leads. And the enclosure was dented.

So instead of returning the thing, I made it better. I replaced the aluminum enclosure with this printed box, which improves the design in several respects, and also serves as a general purpose replacement part. Features:

  • Identical dimensions to the standard form-factor (drop-in replacement)
  • Designed to use threaded brass heat-set inserts for strength and longevity
  • Provides countersunk holes for mounting the input-voltage switch and heatsinks
  • Recessed rectangular areas for applying custom-printed information labels
  • Exclusively uses metric (M3 and M4) button head socket screws
  • Design has been tested and refined over several printed iterations

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2 mm

Notes:

Has been printed on various printers with 0.2 mm layers and 4 exterior walls. Recommend using a strong material like PLA/PHA blend, but regular PLA should be ok too. Print one top part and one bottom part.

Additional required parts and tools:

  • (17x) M3 Button Head Socket Screw, 6 mm
  • (2x) M3 Button Head Socket Screw, 14 mm
  • (4x) M4 Button Head Socket Screw, 20 mm
  • (11x) M3 Threaded Insert, IUBB-M3-1
  • (8x) M4 Threaded Insert, IUB-M4-1
  • Soldering Iron
  • 2 mm Hex Key
  • 2.5 mm Hex Key

The label files are designed to be printed on a standard 4 x 6 inch thermal label printer, such as the Zebra LP2844. The PSD source file is included so you can modify the labels if you need to.

I also recommend having some thermal paste on-hand for when you reassemble the heatsinks on the PSU's main board. I don't believe the fact that the printed case is plastic (as opposed to the original being aluminum) will cause any issues. The stock aluminum block heatsinks are doing most of the heat dissipation along with the fan, and the plastic enclosure has so far only ever become slightly warm under full load.

Somehow I managed to break the unit's stock fan, so it was replaced with this one.

I also noticed that despite having the proper holes for fuse holders on the PCB, the board's fuse was just soldered on directly, so I replaced those bits too.

There was also a large bridge rectifier surrounded by the silkscreen outline of a heatsink, but no heatsink present, so I installed this heatsink on there just for the hell of it.

I'm not sure how much these sorts of power supplies vary from model to model (screw locations, PCB layout, cooling systems, etc.) so your mileage may vary, but this design should provide a decent jumping-off point anyway. I also neglected to include any side-mounting holes in this version since I didn't need them and they would have complicated the internal clearances.

The original SketchUp master file is included, which could be helpful for making any modifications or for reference during reassembly of the unit.

description.text:
I was looking for a filament spool that didn't use a lot of filament, and was somewhat modular.

In Canada, which is the red-headed-stepchild of the USA, metric hardware is hard to find. I already had a bunch of 3/8 ID 7/8 OD bearings and 3/8" threaded rod. These bearings and rods are very close to 608 bearings and 8mm rod. In fact to make this I just enlarged a 608 spool 104%. You could probably print it as is, and glue in 608 bearings, or try printing at 97% scale or so.

I "borrowed" the spool
http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2137117

from

http://www.thingiverse.com/EJ160

When I first printed a copy, I didn't like how sharp the one side of the spool was, and I had a hell of a time getting the threads to work. I thickened the side of the spool and enlarged the nut to make it fit better.

I also wanted to use this in my dehydrator, as two rolls stacked while I print (www.printdry.com dehydrator.) So I made one bolt that was shorter that would fit most 1KG rolls.

I added a retaining ring to keep the bearing from slipping in the tube. I probably could have added it to the tube, but that would have been harder to print, and using less filament was the goal here.

There are two nut sizes for different spool hole diameters.

I added spacers so two rolls being used at once, by more then one printer or extruder shouldn't effect each other. Of course you can make the spacer shorter or longer by extending the Z scale in your slicer.

description.text:
Logitech G27 shifter is really arcadey feel so I made this to stiffen up the shift feel. The feel can be stiffened further if the 'bumps' on the slider piece are scaled up or the side walls are 1 layer thicker each. The feel change is most noticeable when going to 1st or 6th gear (and reverse).

The 'leather' boot must be screwed back in place. It will require some pulling to fit it over the edges to make a super tight fitment.

EDIT: There is SOME success to be made with the G29 shifter. Thanks Salvadoor for posting a photo! Frende21 stated that the front 2 screws do NOT fit back on with this mod on the G29 shifter but that should all the rest to fit on. If I ever get my hands on a G29 I will redesign one specifically for that. Chances are slim though.

Separate parts in Separate Planes The idea for this project was based on the need to have multiple parts move in separate planes of motion. As seeing that wheels need to move in a perpendicular plane from the propeller. This can also be used to explain to History students why many early aircraft were mostly designed with two wings including the Wright Flyer.

The Multi-plane Test (Project) Before you as teacher tell tour students to create, you as a teacher should try and design something that has features that cam move in separate planes of motion. For example, a helicopter has 3 sets of objects that move in 3 planes of motion. The is the main rotor moves in the Z axis of motion(up/down), the tail rotor moves in the X axis of motion(left/right), and the wheels that move the Y axis of motion(forwards/backwards). You as a teacher should start this project by showing how to use the CAD software by designing a few small parts. Instruct your students design and create any sort of vehicle that contain objects that spin/turn/wobble/rotate in more than one plane of motion. First: Give each student three sheets of graph paper, and one sheet of isometric graph paper and a ruler. Using the 3 sheets of graph paper, have students draw a top, front, and side view of their object. Have them dimension each drawing make sure to include proper units, inches or centimeters. Second: Give each student the isometric graph paper and a ruler and redraw their design although this time it will be in three dimensions. Third: If computers are available with design software have each student take their drawings to the computer and have them render the design in three dimensions. Fourth: Show students historical examples of multi-planed motion from the past and how the designers of decades past solved these problems. Examples include aeroplanes, hydroplanes, helicopters, hovercraft, etc. Fith: Have each student submit their design for printing
Sixth Seventh: Have students scan all three graph paper drawings into the teachers computer; the students will keep these. Eighth: The teacher will send students their Cad files via email/UPS/FED-EX/Carrier Pigeon with USB flash drive. Encourage your students to work in small groups and to exchange ideas with each other.
You will be surprised by the diversity of designs from all students. Ninth: Print out every students design on your schools 3D printer/Lazer Cutter/CNC Mill, along with the top,side,front, and isometric views on a laserject/inkjet printer Have your students keep you apprised of their projects. At least three class meetings should be held to have students critique each others designs and gain inspiration from other students.

Materials and stuff needed You will need the following: (1) - 8.5" X 11" printing paper, 8.5" X 11"graph paper, and 8.5" X 11" isometric graph paper, or A4 printing paper, A4 graphing paper, and A4 isometric graph paper. Paper size will depend on region and country. (2) - Measuring sticks, angle finders, calipers, compasses(measuring kind, not directional). (3) - Computers with design or CAD software. (4)-Rapid prototyping hardware; such as 3D printers, LAZER cutters, CNC mills. (5)(Optional) - If your on a budget, Hot glue, Glue sticks, Elmers glue, paper, and yard sticks/meter sticks. (6) - Inkjet/Lazerjet printer/Printing Press/pencil and paper. (7)(Optional) - Students with portable or home computers have the ability download software compatible with the current file type and can work on this project on their own time.

description.text:
This is the early stages of an idea. The general idea is to apply techniques used in the dairy industry for going on the past century to the lacklustre human equivalents available today. Motivated by my wife's present frustrations with the technology and my own frustrations with the profiteering in the local maternity market.

It is not too disimilar to current products available. The addition of a one-way valve on the end of the collection tube, using the vacuum inlet on the shield side, leaving the other open as a vent and it would function the same.

Rather than simply applying a pulsating vacuum to a rigid cup, which will tend to engorge tissue and cause discomfort over time, the goal is to apply a more natural alternating mechanical compression and suction. In a contemporary milking machine, this is achieved by the use of a flexible teat cup liner and two sources of vacuum, one constant and the other pulsating.

Another notable advantage of a printable design is the possibility of customization. I suspect many problems experienced would reduce to a poor fitting device. There is also a myriad of bottle thread sizes even from the same brand. Most parameters affecting the size and shape are now customizable.

Printer:

Custom Delta

Supports:

No

Notes:

Added some extra support to reduce the worst of the overhang when printing shield side down

The plan is to use a flexible tube liner such as surgical latex tubing to act as the teat cup liner. The tube would be stretched around the internal spout of the collection tube and fastened by a suitable hose clamp or a cable tie. The other end will pass through the collection tube and hopefully stretch out and around the breast shield and be held in place by its own elasticity or another cable tie if required. The use of a liner also prevents the collected milk coming into contact with whatever low grade plastic is used for printing.

To achieve an air tight container, a suitable coating may be required. Wax comes to mind as I've used it to seal prints before, but would probably wash off during sterilisation. I'm currently looking for a food safe epoxy which will also allow for sterilization.

For the first attempt, I plan to use a commercial pulsating vacuum pump which will be split two ways. The port leading to inside the breast cup will pass the pulsating vacuum directly through, while the other will traverse a one-way valve en route to the closed collection container such that vacuum will accumulate up to the peak negative pressure provided by the pump.

The streght of the part comes by the steel M8 thread that is inside the hanger. You need to have one anchor bolt like you see on the picture, or you can make with some chemical anchor a normal steel thread in to the wall.

To mount this place the thread in the wall and fix them with a washer and a M8 nut. Than you put also a m8 nut in to the hanger. This is a nice fit and you maybe need to put the m8 nut with a other bolt and screw the nut in to place. after that it is just screwing the hanger in place.

the part that is on the wall have a hole for the wall nut. So i make a very big fillet to go from the big hole to the small hole. Normally if your printer is do some nice overhangs you don't need any support. A small lose thread is no problem because you don't see this part normally.

description.text:
This is the start of my Gingery Lathe project.

My goal is to print all of the patterns using my 3D printer. I'm well on my way ;)

This Thing will change over time with new models being added and just a whole lot of videos showing how I cast them and put the things together.

All of my videos are set up by page number in the Gingery Lathe book. check back as I will upload more videos as I make more parts ;)

pg 4-16 - Introduction - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WeuH0iAFxJI&t=25s
pg 17 to 21 - Lathe bed - Part 1 - https://youtu.be/3ggprnnLjfQ
pg 17 to 21 - Lathe bed - Part 2 - https://youtu.be/vYoBmLPnuLI
pg 22 to 23 - Special Flask - https://youtu.be/WF8cvci76tw
Tips #1 - Sand Mulling - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=UxtHzY-IYSg
Tips #2 - Volume Calculations - https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SLILDcpUGTM
pg 23 to 24 - Bed casting - https://youtu.be/KGj0eY7qNiE
pg 25 - Bed Cleanup - Part 1 - https://youtu.be/z_51WLNqqAY

Printer Brand:

Prusa

Printer:

Prusa Clone

Resolution:

.3

20%

Notes:

Print two of each part. Scale the parts up to accommodate for shrinkage. I used 103% on these parts and that was a little too much. I will experiment with 102% next.

The bed parts print easy and should be printed as they sit, upside down, which will give you a nice smooth surface for the top of the bed.

The foot should be printed right side up with supports.

Use enough infill that when rammed into the casting flask it will not deform the model. I find 20% infill to be plenty.

Sand your patterns. I used first 60grit paper, and then 80grit sanding for very short periods of time and moving onto another spot so the plastic doesn't overheat when sanding.

Make Cookies, Sand the pattern, cast the pattern.

I'm using the patterns as a mold to make sand cores as well as a casting pattern. Making sand cores simplifies the casting process for these parts.

Make your sand cores before you glue the bed parts together.

I used JB Weld to glue my bed parts together. I used a reference plate to ensure that the parts were true and flat during my glue up process.

When sanding, do not sand the top of the bed or the insides of the patterns. You only need to sand the areas which come in contact with the casting sand.

This video shows you how to make sand cores using the model as a mold for the cores. After you've made your sand cores, it is time to glue the bed parts together. You'll need a good flat surface and a straight edge to do this. A special flask is required for the lathe bed. DIY casting sand needs to have a mulling step. You already have everything you need to exactly calculate the weight of aluminum you will need. It is finally time to pour some molten metal! :D Here is a rough clean up of the cast bed. Next comes the hand scraping.

title: Mr2web's Anet A3S Fan ring
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
After trying other Anet A3 fan rings I decides to create my own design due to I was not pleased with the ones I did print and tried. These other did not fit my printer as the ring was not sitting horizontally flat and not distributing the airflow that even across the ring. One was generating a whistling sound that was killing my ears and so on...

I'm very pleased with the result of this fan ring and I hope anyone else could enjoy a silent-ish and perfectly horizontal fan ring for the Anet A3S printer.

The fan ring was designed for the Anet A3S printer manufactured in Marsh 2017.

This was a great project to learn the Fusion 360 software as well learning to design for 3D printing. This was my absolute first design.

Enjoy! :-D

Printer:

Anet A3S

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1-0.2mm

Infill:

20%

Notes:

Shell->Wall thickness: 0.8mm
Shell->Top/Bottom thickness: 0.8mm

Air flow

Well, one of the reasons I felt the need to design my own fan ring was the lack of even air flow with other rings I have tried out.
This ring has, well in my own opinion, a more even air flow across the ring then other rings I have tried out. This is due to the two barriers in the air flow entrance to the actual ring. These will direct the air flow to flow more in line with the ring shape rather then just hitting the first nozzle holes and let the access air to spread out into the ring. This did give that the majority of the air did flow through the three nozzle holes closes to the entry point to the ring rather then spreading more evenly across the ring. Please see the attached image for where these barriers are located.

I also angled the nozzle holes to target the air flow just below the extruder nozzle tip to provide the best cooling of the filament as quickly as possible after it have been passed through the extruder nozzle.

The shape of the ring nozzle holes has been design to prevent noise.

Use a near-solid infill for maximum compression strength (but not 100%). I chose rectilinear because various studies have shown that to be the strongest over honeycomb, etc, and it prints the fastest. Do not turn on supports (no way to clear from inner cavity) - part was designed to print without supports. Once print is complete, the outer support cylinder will easily peel off.

vapor treatment

Although this weakens the strength of the part a bit (8-20% depending on who's study you read), I felt vapor treatment was necessary to ensure the surface is water-tight so the oil won't leak out slowly and rain won't leak in. To get the vapor to the inner surface where it was needed I had to add a fan to the chamber to move the air around (first attempt without the fan only treated the outer surfaces). Make sure you use a brushless (spark free) fan!

Filling

It is a little tricky getting the oil into the cavity. I ended up bending a piece of tubing to reach over the lip. Add about 20ml (part holds about 25ml before overflowing).

description.text:
I've created an offset globe spinner. It does at the name implies, spins on an offset of circles around a sphere. I printed this using PVA (water soluble supports). But you can do as your mileage sees fit.

This iteration gives <1mm clearance for the posts that coincide with the other rings. It cannot be taken apart and must be printed as is.

STL and F3D files attached for you designing pleasure

ENJOY!
TameGorilla

Support Removal

If you are using water soluble supports (PVA)... grab a nice heated bath and be prepared to wait.

Otherwise let me know how traditional material supports worked for you.

Fusion 360

I used Fusion 360 to create this geometry.

Whatsa' Happenin'

::5/4/2017::
Printed at highest resolution possible with ULTIMAKER 3, using dissolvable supports and CURA defaults. The post on the globe portion is a bit thin and must be handled with care. I used my immersion circulator to break up supports. It took about 36 hours. I would suggest scaling the object AND creating shorter posts with wider diameter. Possibly add chamfer for angular look or a 2 - 5 mm fillet. PLEASE LET ITEM COOL ALL THE WAY IF USING IMMERSION CIRCULATOR TO BREAK UP THE PVA SUPPORTS. If you are using nylon, taulman 910 / bridge, or some other tough material use you judgment.

::5/3/2017::
After 2+ days after initial print (17+ hours) the PVA supports are just about gone. I utilize my sous vide setup with a nozzle modifier to direct the 35C water directly at the support. Previous I allowed the part to circulate... that took WAY too long as the part was moving WITH the water versus against it. I will post pics after rough build is complete.

This is an enclosure that is held in place by magnets that hold to the sides of the Z Tower.
It is an easy to produce enclosure using 2mm acrylic sheet.
Note that I have produced the front cover to be close to the display panel and this looses a small amount of the build plate but you can increase the measurement of you side pieces, i will produce 2 small side inserts that can be added for the few times that full print area use is required.

Please note that the printer is mounted on a Lazy Susan to allow all round access, the Locator Buttons are attached to the wooden base on the Lazy Susan.

This is a 'What Duck' design

For both a front and back cover you will need to print these parts-
4 x Right angled Plate Base Mag Mount

4 x 3 Corner Washer

8 x Washer Plate for Mag mount.

In addition you need
8 Magnets Diameter 12mm x 3mm with countersink.
M3 Screws x 12mm long, 56 off
M3 Nuts or Nylon lock nuts x 52 off
and 4 small wood screws to attached the W Locator Button to a base.
As well as a 2mm Acrylic Sheet.
I have not given the measurements of the acrylic sheet panels as this may vary slightly but you will be able to take measurements of you printer, also allow for the movement of the buildplate on the front and back panels making cutouts to suit. Be sure to remove the burrs and sharp edges from the acrylic sheet after cutting.
(Thin acrylic sheet can be scored and then snapped to cut it, so basic tools can be used to produce this cover).
The front top piece has a large gap to allow for the filament.

The bottom corners can also accept the same magnets so that instead of the button a steel screw can be countersink into the wooden base and all locations are then magnetic.

Edited 25th May 2017.
The magnets can either be bonded in position or held by M4 x 10 Countersunk screws (caution don't over tighten as the force can fracture the magnets)
Edited 8th August 2017
Added the missing L bracket patrs

I designed this case to fit the minimum foot print of the printer and fit on a 400x400mm lazy Susan base for all round access.
This prevents pets and children getting too close to hot parts, as well as providing a draft excluder for when printing with ABS etc, allowing you to leave the printer unattended and hopefully safe from paws etc.

The two halfs allow for just the front or back to be removed.
The Perspex needs to be cut to suit your requirements, and to allow for the Y movement of your build-plate, and if you have Z bracing fitted.
The edges of the Perspex can be taped or bonded as required, or just left held by the mounts etc.

description.text:
These magnetic clamps are designed so that you can glue perfect 90 degree angles. Since we so regularly need to glue parts in our hobby, I designed these after seeing them used on Terranscapes.

In order to ensure the resulting part is strong, it needs to be tuned to your specific printer. The reason is, we want the wall thickness to be an exact multiplier of the nozzle so that it creates a really strong wall. I strongly recommend you customize your prints if your nozzle is any size other then 0.4mm (which is my printer's nozzle, and thus the size on all the stls).

With stronger magnets you will probably want 3 walls of thickness, but with weaker ones you will do fine with 2. I've included a bunch of videos below testing the clamps at various strengths, and the original review that gave me the idea.

For instructions on how to get started with OpenForge, take a look at our tutorials.

OpenForge is now a patron supported project. I use the resources that my patrons give me in order to get the resources to let me create more sophisticated tiles with a greater level of detail. Please, support me, and I’ll deliver an ongoing stream of awesome gaming terrain. You can find more about OpenForge and Masterwork Tools at our:

  • Online catalog and backer site
  • Website
  • Forums (Mostly we use facebook now)
  • Twitter

Deciding on magnets

With an N42 1"x1/8"x1/8" magnet we are getting a bit over 2 lbs. At $0.74/piece, you can make this clamp for $2.96. These are a bit weak (but can still work) with tiles, but would be wonderful with thin strips of wood, or smaller parts like the docks construction kit pieces.

With an N42 1"x1/8"x1/4" magnet we are getting a bit over 2 lbs. At $1.26/piece, you can make this clamp for $5.04. I recommend this set for most tiles. They are strong and will hold the tile while you glue.

With an N42 1"x1/4"x1/4" magnet we can get a bit over 5 lbs. At $2.14/piece, you can make this clamp for $8.56. These monsters are great, but on normal tiles, they are so strong they repel each other so it makes them a little harder to use on something 2 inches x 2 inches like most tiles.

If you want to go even stronger, you can get N52 for $2.75/piece for $11/clamp. I estimate these should give about 6.25 lbs of clamping force.

Thing is, testing these with my tiles, I think even the cheapest option is still useful, but the stronger ones are even better. And if what you want to glue is thin wood, the lighter touch is probably preferable. I personally made two of each strength.

E-bay and others sell these little build yourself C51 3 - 5 V electronic clocks. Currently at time of writing they are £1.67 inc Post so I got one to play with. I made one and wanted a little case for it so I knocked one up in Tinkercad.

It's not perfect and maybe if someone was more finicky than me they may want to use the STL model I have included to move the holes for the setting buttons 1mm to the right along with the buzzer 1 mm up (or put a small grate across the hole, I don't know).

I removed the connector block from the component board as this stuck up too much and just soldered two wires to the back for power and left holes for these to come out the back. Maybe another version could have 2 x AA battery compartment or a slot to fit a USB connector (I don't have any at this time although when I do I may add this). Anyway at this time the wires stick out and I was thinking of just soldering these to a cut off USB C for power from my computer.

After I made the box for it (see below how) I wanted it to stand at an angle so I just made a triangle thing for it to stand in with a 12 degree angle up for better viewing on a desk. this file is included as base if you wish to use it.

Created a rough model of the shape and size of the completed electronic kit assembled in Tinkercad. I then made a box and added the Model as a "hole" and fitted it into the box aligning it on the X and Y plane but keeping it flat with the base of the Z surface.
I made another box for the back and made it the same outside dimensions as my component holding box but only 4mm high so it could function as a back panel.
I raised the component box off the Z plane and turned that into a hole and aligned it with the back shape.
Lowering the component box hole over the back panel shape I aligned it so it was square on X and Y planes but left 2mm of the back panel showing between the Z plane surface and the bottom of the upper hole component box shape.
I made a copy of the upper box by selecting it and control C control V shortcuts then moved the copy over to the side out the way.
I joined the bottom and top box so afterwards I was left with a 2mm high panel with a raised 2mm inner rim.
I then adjusted the copied top box hole model by 0.2 mm in size making it just a little smaller and aligned that on the X,Y planes again making it raised 2mm from the Z surface.
This gave the fitting of the box back a little wriggle room.
I joined the two items together again this left the bottom panel with a slightly smaller rim for fitting into the original front component box.

This is how I make most of my boxes to fit things in and it seems to work !

description.text:
I replaced my stock LG Watch Style band with what's called a "deployment" band: one that doesn't unbuckle and lie flat. I like the band a lot, but it wouldn't work well with the charger. So I designed this stand.

This charging stand holds the charger securely, and has space for your "deployment"-style band. It's also a stylish way to display your watch!

Printer Brand:

LulzBot

Printer:

Mini

Rafts:

No

Supports:

Yes

Notes:

Print the stand on its side for strength, with the open side of the charger holder facing up to minimize the need for supports (see the attached Cura image). Remember to print with Supports (see the attached printer image).

I printed in PLA.
Remove the support material.

The attached FreeCAD file shows how I broke up the stand design into 4 parts: a 180 degree rotation for most of the charger holder; an extrusion from the charger holder to give something to slide the charger into; a curved bar that lifts the charger holder above the base; and the base.

I chose the radius of the rotation profile to provide a little (0.5mm) clearance between the charger and its holder. I've found this clearance holds the charger snugly, yet makes it easy to remove the charger from the stand.
